"Sanford T.J., Murphy D.M., Thomson D.S., Fox R.W.","Albedo measurements and optical sizing of single aerosol particles",2008,"Aerosol Science and Technology","42","11",,"958","969",,,10.1080/02786820802363827,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-52949097174&partnerID=40&md5=4d7f211f49872298eb2ad08cb9d2b944","NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, Boulder, CO, United States; Cooperative Institute for Research in the Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States; National Institute of Standards and Technology, Boulder, CO, United States; Droplet Measurement Technologies, Boulder, CO, United States; NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, 325 Broadway CSD2, Boulder, CO 80305-3337, United States","Sanford, T.J., NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, Boulder, CO, United States, Cooperative Institute for Research in the Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States, NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, 325 Broadway CSD2, Boulder, CO 80305-3337, United States; Murphy, D.M., NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, Boulder, CO, United States; Thomson, D.S., NOAA Earth System Research Laboratory, Boulder, CO, United States, Cooperative Institute for Research in the Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO, United States, Droplet Measurement Technologies, Boulder, CO, United States; Fox, R.W., National Institute of Standards and Technology, Boulder, CO, United States","Aerosols play an important role in global climate change by their interactions with incoming solar radiation and outgoing longwave radiation from the planetary surface. The climate effects of aerosols depend on their scattering and absorption properties. This article describes the development of an instrument (ASTER: Aerosol Scattering To Extinction Ratio) that simultaneously measures the scattering and extinction of single aerosol particles. ASTER uses a high-Q cavity to amplify the extinction signal and innovative optics to collect the scattered light. It can distinguish many partially absorbing particles from a few black ones even if the bulk absorption is the same. Optical sizing and single-scattering albedo measurements were made for laboratory-generated particles with diameters from about 300 nanometers to above one micrometer. Using this prototype instrument, changes in albedo for single particles of 20% or greater were detected by measurement of the scattering and extinction. Optical sizing of the individual particles to within ∼50 nm was accomplished using the ratio of the forward scattered light to the total scattering. Initial measurements of laboratory air showed a mode of highly absorbing particles. This article reports design and early laboratory tests on ASTER. Copyright © American Association for Aerosol Research.",,"Absorption; Air pollution; Atmospheric aerosols; Atomizers; Climate change; Ketones; Light; Light scattering; Scattering; Solar radiation; Sun; Thickness measurement; Absorbing particles; Aerosol particles; Aerosol scattering; Albedo measurements; Bulk absorption; Climate effects; Extinction ratio; Global climate changes; high-Q cavity; Individual particles; Laboratory testing; Optical-; Outgoing longwave radiation; Planetary surfaces; Prototype instruments; Scattered light; Scattering and absorption; Single particles; Single scattering albedos; Total scattering; Aerosols; aerosol; air analysis; albedo; article; atmosphere; diode laser; light absorption; light scattering; optics; particle size; priority journal",,,,,,"Ackerman, T.P., Toon, O.B., Absorption of Visible Radiation in Atmosphere Containing Mixtures of Absorbing and Nonabsorbing Particles (1981) Appl. Opt, 20, pp. 3661-3668; Andreae, M.O., Gelencser, A., Black Carbon or Brown Carbon? The Nature of Light-Absorbing Carbonaceous Aerosols (2006) Atmos. Chem. Phys. Discuss, 6, pp. 3419-3463; Arnott, W.P., Moosmuller, H., Rogers, C.F., Jin, T.F., Bruch, R., Photoacoustic Spectrometer for Measuring